  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Funeral Oration for Master Yangchon, the Meritorious Minister Gwon
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven and earth gathered their essence; the mountains descended their divine presence. Thus was born a sage, transcendent and beyond all measure. Above, he took the Way of Confucius and Mencius as his guide; below, he inherited the learning of Zhou Dunyi and the Cheng brothers. He penetrated the mysteries of heaven, earth, and the dual forces; he plumbed the depths of nature, destiny, and principle. Straight as a plumb line, level as a builder's rule, round as a compass, square as a set square. His countenance bore the gentle radiance of spring wind; his writings shone with the brilliance of Mount Tai and the Northern Star. He became the venerable master whom scholars revered, the pillar and cornerstone upon which the realm relied. Rich in righteousness and achievement, profound in word and virtue, the sovereign drew upon his talents as upon the rain in drought; the nation depended upon him for its fortune and peril.

    Yet sorrow—before his talents could be fully employed, that bright flame was suddenly extinguished. Mount Tai has crumbled; grief spreads far and near. The state has lost its worthy arm; anguish pierces the imperial heart. Is this the inscrutable way of heaven? Or is it that the people lack the blessing of fortune?

    Alas! We who admired his teachings and walked in his shadow, who gathered close as his disciples—now the sage has departed and the great beam has snapped. Where shall we turn? Where shall we place our trust? The final parting comes with its ancient rites; the tomb awaits its appointed day. The transmission of our Way seems now cut short. Before the spirit-box we offer these meager sacrifices, tears falling to wet our robes. If your departed spirit yet remains, we pray you receive this humble offering. Alas, how sorrowful is this day.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yangchon (陽村) and Gwon (權) refer to the deceased being honored; this is a cenotaph or funeral oration following Confucian rites
  - key: ''
    value: The references to Confucius and Mencius (Zou-Lu) and Zhou Dunyi and the Cheng brothers (Lian-Luo) invoke the intellectual lineage of Neo-Confucianism
  - key: ''
    value: The geometric tools (plumb line, rule, compass, set square) are traditional metaphors for moral rectitude and principle
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Tai and the Northern Star are classical symbols of supreme authority and constancy
